element_texts.text:
Dear Brother Issac
I have just returned from Hampden, whither we felt obliged to go to see about our girl, as soon as we found Ellen was really going to leave us Thursday-was much disappointed to find you gone - you had only been gone ten minutes, Ellen said - and you forgot your little girl, I was sure of seeing you again I had ever so many things to say. 
It is well that you did go Tuesday isn't it? Now won't it be so bad going that we can't go to Milo?
Ellen left us for good yesterday p.m., expecting to start for Minn. today, but I hardly think the boats got in yesterday. The poor girl cried sadly. You should have seen her hold Perci away & look in his face as if she

never meant to forget him, then hold his hands in both of hers and look at him again, without hardly speaking at all.  It seemed to distress her that he wouldn't feel bad about her going.  He would say over after her "Nellens going away -never, never see Perci any more", but he didn't feel it as she wanted him to. We shall never see her like again in many aspects- I couldn't help crying myself- From all accounts, we are likely to be fortunate in the next girl- I suppose she cannot come till next week, Little Charlotte Chalmers is staying with me a few days - she is nicely helpful & very pleasant. I gave Perci catnip tea yesterday & I cut his gums in eight places without his making a word of objection  Three great double teeth just ready to come through & very much swollen - He slept much more quietly last night - I felt so anxious
